title: For Sale:  Mosin-Nagant M91/30 7.62X54R
postcontent:
For Sale is a "classic" WWII-era Mosin Nagant Model 91/30 rifle. These rifles were stored in the Ukraine by the former Soviet Union, refinished and sent to the U.S. I have owned and shot this rifle for the last 5 years. This bolt-action firearm is in remarkably good condition with all the cosmoline long-since removed. Chambered in 7.62x54R, a caliber that falls between the American .308 and .30-06 in power and ballistics, these rifles are great shooters and suitable for vintage military matches or hunting big game. Each has a top-loading five-round magazine. Rear sights are adjustable for elevation and outfitted with range marks in meters. Front sights are military post-and-globe style. You can mount a scout scope on this beast using a picatinny adapter in place of the rear sight for even better long range accuracy. This rifle comes complete with bayonet, sling and original field maintenance kit. I'll also throw in a few boxes of ammo so you can take it to the range right away. You can usually find additional ammo online for anywhere from $0.20 to $0.30 per round if you buy in bulk which makes this a great range gun (incredible power to cost ratio).
I priced it the same as you can find online, but if you're local you can save both tax and shipping. And if you're not local, sorry I'm not interested in shipping or accepting online payments/transferring the gun out-of-state. Also please bring a valid driver's license as WA transfer paperwork will be filed.

title: For Sale:  Revolver Tuning
postcontent:
So far I have come across no one in Birmingham that tunes revolvers. I graduated the Colorado School of Trades Gunsmith Program this past year and have extensive practice tuning Colts, SA Revolvers of the Colt Design, Rugers, S&W's, Webleys, Dan Wessons, Taurus's, Ect. 

  In school I learned how to change barrels, cut forcing cones to shoot better with Hard cast or Lead Cast bullets. Along with fitting any part inside of a revolver. Most revolvers can be tuned or repaired with a minimum of tools, but Taurus revolvers often require ebay shopping, or finding a parts gun to buy used parts from. Reason being is Taurus does not sell their parts directly to the customer or even a gunsmith. All other wheelguns are relatively easy to fix. 

  For revolver tuning the fee is 60$.
For a full detailed disassembly cleaning and oiling and tuning the fee is 90$. 

Traditional Rust Bluing of a Revolver is 180$ This does not include polishing. 

Polishing is all done by hand and is 80$ per hour. 80$ per hour covers expendable tools like polishing stones, emery cloth, file use, and hand numbing work.

 It is always best to bring in a well cleaned revolver, but if you must have me clean it then you will pay for it. As of yet I know of no one that can tune a revolver so I'm offering this service to fill any voids in repairs. I personally love hunting with my Dan wesson 44, and my S&W 357, and carry my Ruger S. Six 22mag every time I'm working my land, so I can understand the frustration with folks having to send their pistols off to be worked on. This service often times can be accomplished within 48 hours, If parts need to be ordered a repair time will be quoted and adhered to before the service begins. 

 I will not claim to make 60$ per hour. Often times it takes me a couple hours to tune a revolver and longer to clean one. Sometimes special screw drivers are required to be made just to service these gems. These skills are a dying art and something that should not be forgotten. Auto repairs run 100$+ per hour, so why would you pay a gunsmith 20$ per hour to tune a machine that may blow up in your hand?

  I am a professional craftsman, and will operate as such. I do not do rush orders and never will. Each firearm regardless of price or make will receive my complete care and attention. Prices will be quoted before service and will be witnessed by the customer. Retrieval of a repaired pistol will be after service is paid for. 

I will not ship or receive arms under my FFL license. 

I look forward to hearing from you and helping you resolve any issues with your sixgun. God Bless and Happy Shooting

postcontent:
I have for sale a derringer made in 1967. It was imported and sold through herter's of weseca minn. when they were in business from the late 1800s up till 1981 when they filed bankruptcy. This one is in 22lr caliber. Has steel hammer, trigger, pins, screws and barrel inset into the casting. Not thin liners like a lot of the new derringers have but actual steel barrels inset into barrel casting. 
Has the eagle over N proof marks for nitro proofed. For smokeless powder. Also has the ULM proof house mark which is the stag antler and date of 67 next to it. Meaning it was proofed in 1967 when it was made. 
For anyone not familiar with the ulm proof house they are the ones who HK exclusively goes through and walther uses them as well as far back as WWII. They are a quality proofhouse and proof quality firearms in return. 
Marked Western Derringer, Made in Germany. Not made by rohm either. It has the Kaschie factory stamp under the grip.

title: For Sale/Trade:  800 Rounds Federal HST .40S&W JHP
postcontent:
Best CCW Ammo you can buy!

For sale/trade is 800 rounds of Federal HST 155gr JHP for a .40S&W. Current retail price on this is between $1.25/round and $1.50/round - I am only asking $1.00 per round for cash offers.

Federal released its Hydra-Shok line of ammunition to capture the law enforcement market years ago, and while it was a good round - it proved troublesome when going through barriers before reaching its target - clogging much of the time.

Federal corrected the problem by introducing a line known as HST, and it was tested extensively by the FBI upon its release in .40 caliber, and adopted as their ammunition after blowing the tests out of the water. This is currently the only ammunition I will carry as I feel like it is the only ammunition to hold a candle to the famous "Black Talon".

It's easy to find the much less desirable Hydra-Shok ammunition on the shelf, and many people are intrigued by the "post" inside the hollow point. If you do the research, and I suggest you do, you will find that HST is extremely tough to beat.

That's why HST has almost never (in my experience) been for sale on the shelves at your local gun shop - I have only ever found it online, for a premium price, and in small or limited quantities. I have recently switched to a different caliber for my preferred CCW and cannot find anywhere that sells HST in bulk, must less a place with a single box in stock right now.

I live in Puyallup, but will be willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet - or even ship if you want to pay for shipping. 

Take a look here for FBI Protocol test results on this ammunition
http://le.atk.com/ammunition/federal/handgun/details.aspx?id=567

title: For Sale:  Ruger 10/22 with green and yellow laminated stock, aluminum parts
postcontent:
This is a one of a kind Ruger 10/22 with a green/yellow laminated stock. When Ruger started making laminated stocks, they made up a bunch of samples and only chose a select few. This is one of the ones that wasn't chosen.

This is an older style with the aluminum barrel band, trigger guard, trigger, and magazine release. The inside of the receiver is also cast then MILLED as opposed to just cast and called good, so it has a very smooth action. The hammer and sear in these older rifles were also mated for each other making for a really nice trigger. This is a much higher quality rifle than what they make today.

Comes with 1 10 round magazine and a Tasco 3x9x40 scope.

$250 firm.
